Fixed PHP-423: MongoDate support for 64-bit timestamps on 32-bit systems.

I can't create a test case as there is no way to create a "larger" timestamp on
32 bit platforms in the first place. After this change, MongoDate will also
show that MongoDB really only supports milliseconds, and not microseconds as
MongoDate implies. This means that a var_dump just after creation will truncate
to three decimals. This is a tiny BC break, but IMO it is more correct to do it
like this, as it reflects how it really works.

Simple scopes.

Scopes can be defined similar to a where, like:

User::scope("first_level",array("level"=>1));
$users = User::first_level();

A very important point here is that they need to be called as methods (like
static methods, like above). Trying to call them as attributes, like

User::first_level

won't work because that way they seems to be class constants.

Chained scopes will come. Just need to send a already created builder to
